! Year !! Month and date !! Event type !! Details
|-
| 1946 || || || {{w|Milton Friedman}} [[wikipedia:Milton Friedman#University of Chicago|accepts]] an offer to teach at the {{w|University of Chicago}}.
|-
| 1946 || {{dts|March 7}} || || The {{w|Foundation for Economic Education}}, a libertarian think tank, is founded.
|-
| 1947 || || || The {{w|Mont Pelerin Society}} is formed. "The society advocates freedom of expression, free market economic policies, the political values of an open society." Some of its founders are prominent libertarians.
|-
| 1949 || {{dts|October 1}} || || {{w|George Mason University}} (GMU) is established. The GMU economics department would become known for its concentration of free-market-oriented thinkers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/sports/sports_nut/2006/03/the_secret_of_george_mason.html |first1=Peter |last1=Boettke |first2=Alexander |last2=Tabarrok |title=The real secret of George Mason University. |publisher=Slate Magazine |date=March 28, 2006 |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>
|-
| 1950 || {{dts|October 2}} || || The first issue of ''{{w|The Freeman}}'', a libertarian magazine, is published.
|-
| 1950s || || || The term "{{w|Chicago school of economics}}" is [[wikipedia:History of economic thought#The Chicago school of economics (20th century)|coined]] during this period.
|-
| 1950s–1960s || || || {{w|Ayn Rand}}'s group of close confidants, known as [[w:Objectivist movement#The Collective|the Collective]], meets during this period.
|-
| 1957 || || || {{w|Ayn Rand}}'s novel ''{{w|Atlas Shrugged}}'' is published. The book "contains Rand's most extensive statement of Objectivism in any of her works of fiction".
|-
| 1960 || || || {{w|Liberty Fund}}, a libertarian non-profit foundation, is established.
|-
| 1961 || || || [[wikipedia:Thomas Szasz|Thomas Szasz]]'s ''{{w|The Myth of Mental Illness}}'' is published. The book "criticizes psychiatry and argues against the concept of mental illness".
|-
| 1961 || || || The {{w|Institute for Humane Studies}}, a libertarian non-profit organization, is founded.
|-
| 1962 || || || {{w|Milton Friedman}}'s book ''{{w|Capitalism and Freedom}}'' is published. "Friedman argues for economic freedom as a precondition for political freedom. He defines 'liberal' in European Enlightenment terms, contrasting with an American usage that he believes has been corrupted since the Great Depression. His views are especially popular among American conservatives and libertarians."
|-
| 1966 || || || ''{{w|The Moon Is a Harsh Mistress}}'', a {{w|libertarian science fiction}} novel by {{w|Robert A. Heinlein}}, is published. The book popularizes the "{{w|There ain't no such thing as a free lunch}}" adage.
|-
| 1966 || || || ''{{w|Capitalism: The Unknown Ideal}}'' by {{w|Ayn Rand}} (with additional essays by others) is published.
|-
| 1968 || {{dts|May}} || || The first issue of ''[[wikipedia:Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'', a libertarian monthly magazine, is published.
|-
| 1970 || || || ''{{w|The Market for Liberty}}'', an anarcho-capitalist book by Linda and Morris Tannehill, is published.
|-
| 1971 || {{dts|December 11}} || || The United States [[wikipedia:Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] (LP) officially forms.
|-
| 1972 || || || ''{{w|Libertarian Review}}'', a libertarian magazine, is established. It would be published until 1981.
|-
| 1973 || || || {{w|David D. Friedman}}'s ''{{w|The Machinery of Freedom}}'' is published.
|-
| 1973 || || || {{w|Murray Rothbard}}'s ''{{w|For a New Liberty}}'' is published. The book argues for anarcho-capitalism.
|-
| 1973 || {{dts|September 11}} || || The {{w|1973 Chilean coup d'état}} takes place. The coup leads to rule of {{w|Augusto Pinochet}}, whose military government implements free-market-oriented policies under the influence of the {{w|Chicago Boys}}.
|-
| 1974 || || || {{w|Robert Nozick}}'s ''{{w|Anarchy, State, and Utopia}}'' is published. The book argues in favor of a minimal state.
|-
| 1974 || Fall || || The ''Reason Papers'' is founded.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://reasonpapers.com/archives/ |title=Archives |publisher=Reason Papers |accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref> ''Reason Papers' describes itself as "a forum for inquiry and debate across a wide spectrum of views rather than the instrument of any one ideology, party, or camp" and "is not edited for conformity with any particular philosophical or ideological perspective, is neither aligned with nor endorses any other institution or organization, and receives no funding from any outside source". However, it is hosted by the {{w|Mises Institute}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://reasonpapers.com/ |publisher=Reason Papers |title=A Journal of Interdisciplinary Normative Studies |accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>
|-
| 1974 || {{dts|December}} || || The {{w|Cato Institute}}, a libertarian think tank, is founded as the Charles Koch Foundation.
|-
| 1976 || || || The {{w|Center for Libertarian Studies}}, a "libertarian and anarcho-capitalist oriented educational organization", is founded by {{w|Murray Rothbard}}.
|-
| 1977 || Spring || || The ''{{w|Journal of Libertarian Studies}}'' is established.
|-
| 1977 || {{dts|November 21}} || || The first issue of [[wikipedia:Inquiry (magazine)|Inquiry]], a libertarian magazine, is published.
|-
| 1978 || || || The {{w|Reason Foundation}}, a libertarian think tank, is founded.
|-
| 1978 || || || {{w|Ron Paul newsletters}} begin to be published.
|-
| 1979 || || || The {{w|Prometheus Award}}, an award for {{w|libertarian science fiction}}, is first established.
|-
| 1979 || {{dts|October 16}} || || {{w|J. Neil Schulman}}'s dystopian novel ''{{w|Alongside Night}}'' is published. It contains the [[w:Counter-economics#Origin|first portrayal]] of {{w|counter-economics}} in a book.
|-
| 1980 || || || The {{w|Mercatus Center}}, a "non-profit free-market-oriented research, education, and outreach think tank", is established at {{w|George Mason University}}.
|-
| 1980 || {{dts|October}} || || {{w|Samuel Edward Konkin III}}'s ''{{w|New Libertarian Manifesto}}'' is published. It is the first explanation of Konkin's {{w|agorism}}.
|-
| 1982 || || || {{w|Murray Rothbard}}'s ''{{w|The Ethics of Liberty}}'' is published.
|-
| 1982 || || || The {{w|Ludwig von Mises Institute}} is founded. "Through its publications, the Institute promotes anarcho-capitalist political theory and a form of heterodox economics known as praxeology".
|-
| 1984 || {{dts|March 9}} || || The {{w|Competitive Enterprise Institute}}, a non-profit libertarian think tank, is founded.
|-
| 1984 || {{dts|November}} || || [[w:Charles Murray (political scientist)|Charles Murray]]'s book ''[[w:Losing Ground (book)|Losing Ground]]'' is published. The book is "about the effectiveness of welfare state policies in the United States between 1950 and 1980". The book, while less explicitly libertarian than some of his later work, tries to show that "by most available measures, the late 1960s wave of income transfer programs [&hellip;] did not improve the lives of the poor, and in most cases made them worse off".<ref name="Doherty">{{cite book |title=Radicals for Capitalism: A Freewheeling History of the Modern American Libertarian Movement |author=Brian Doherty |year=2007 |publisher=PublicAffairs}}</ref>
|-
| 1985 || || || The {{w|Ayn Rand Institute}} is founded to promote Objectivism.
|-
| 1985 || || || The {{w|Independence Institute}}, a libertarian think tank based in Denver, Colorado, is founded.
|-
| 1986 || || || The {{w|Independent Institute}}, a libertarian think tank based in Oakland, California, is founded.
|-
| 1990 || || || {{w|Bruce L. Benson}}'s ''{{w|The Enterprise of Law}}'' is published.
|-
| 1991 || || || The {{w|Institute for Justice}} (IJ), a "non-profit libertarian public interest law firm", is founded. IJ is headquartered in {{w|Arlington, Virginia}}.
|-
| 1998 || {{dts|April 2}} || || {{w|Randy Barnett}}'s ''{{w|The Structure of Liberty}}'' is published. The book "offers a libertarian theory of law and politics".
|-
| 1999 || || || The Library of Economics and Liberty (Econlib) is launched.<ref>Based on the copyright notice. The earliest Wayback Machine snapshot is from 2000.</ref>
|-
| 2001 || {{dts|September 1}} || || The {{w|Free State Project}} is formed.
|-
| 2003 || {{dts|January}} || || EconLog launches with {{w|Arnold Kling}} as the sole blogger.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.econlib.org/library/About.html#econlog |title=About Econlib |publisher=Library of Economics and Liberty |accessdate=August 1, 2017}}</ref>
|-
| 2008 || {{dts|July 24}} || || {{w|Students for Liberty}}, a libertarian non-profit organization, is founded.
|-
| 2009 || {{dts|January 22}} || || ''Libertarian Papers'', a "peer-reviewed journal of libertarian scholarship", is established. Its self-described purpose is "to advance scholarly research in disciplines of particular interest to the libertarian community, broadly conceived".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://libertarianpapers.org/about/ |title=Aims and Scope |publisher=Libertarian Papers |accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>
|-
| 2013 || {{dts|January}} || || Philosopher {{w|Michael Huemer}}'s book ''{{w|The Problem of Political Authority}}'' is published. The book first argues for {{w|philosophical anarchism}} starting from "widely shared moral premises", then argues for the viability of {{w|anarcho-capitalism}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://econlog.econlib.org/archives/2013/01/the_problem_of_1.html |author=Bryan Caplan |title=The Problem of Political Authority by Michael Huemer |website=EconLog |publisher=Library of Economics and Liberty |date=January 17, 2013 |accessdate=August 1, 2017 |publisher=[[wikipedia:EconLog|EconLog]]}}</ref>
|-
| 2015 || || || The {{w|Niskanen Center}}, a "think tank that advocates for environmentalism, immigration reform, civil liberties, and a national defense policy based on libertarian principles", is founded. It is based in Washington, D.C.
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|February 3}} || || The {{w|Free State Project}} announces that 20,000 people had signed its statement of intent to move, triggering the move (within five years) to New Hampshire.
